  <section class="card content-block">
    <h2>TL;DR</h2>
    <p>
      I led the redesign of the Consultant ecosystem within Slimming World’s
      digital transformation, grounded in long-term ethnographic research.
    </p>
    <p>
      Xpress Weigh was the first major delivery within the redesigned Consultant
      ecosystem.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Phase 1:</strong> Reduced friction in the legacy member support tool
        — &gt;90% voluntary adoption in six weeks.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Phase 2:</strong> Challenged and redefined the underlying information
        model, securing executive alignment on core priorities.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Pivot:</strong> Adapted the interaction model when group methodology
        changed, without restarting the work.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Validation</strong> & risk reduction: Stress-tested the design through
        immersive usability testing before development.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <h1 class="phase-title"><span>Phase 1</span></h1>
  <section class="card content-block">
    <h2>Problem</h2>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Xpress Weigh&rsquo; was a legacy suite of tools used by Consultants
      to run weekly member groups. Running on Windows tablets, it supported
      enrollment, payments, weight recording and access to member data during
      live sessions.
    </p>

    <p>
      Over time, technical and design debt had resulted in dense, data-heavy
      screens. There was little distinction between data needed in the moment
      and data that was simply available.
    </p>

    <p>
      Weekly groups are fast-paced and emotionally sensitive. Consultants are
      often standing, moving between members and maintaining a human connection.
      In practice, they were navigating the interface while trying to manage the
      room.
    </p>
    <p>
      As Slimming World began exploring broader digital transformation, the
      member-support experience came under scrutiny. The system worked, but it
      wasn&apos;t helping Consultants focus on the conversation in front of
      them.
    </p>

    I was asked to deliver targeted improvements within legacy constraints, with
    a focus on reducing friction during live sessions.
  </section>
  <div class="image-row image-row--full image-row--2">
    <Image
      src={orig1Image}
      alt="Existing screen designs"
      widths={[480, 768, 1024, 1440, 1920]}
      sizes="100vw"
    />
    <Image
      src={orig2Image}
      alt="Existing screen designs"
      widths={[480, 768, 1024, 1440, 1920]}
      sizes="100vw"
    />
  </div>
  <p class="image-row--caption">
    <em>Exisiting solution: </em>Two complex screens were a barrier to natural,
    supportive member conversations.
  </p>
  <section class="card content-block">
    <h2>Approach</h2>
    <p>
      Years of embedded ethnographic exposure — participating in groups as both
      a member and assistant — gave me a grounded understanding of real-world
      use. Targeted one-to-one interviews with Consultants across experience
      levels validated and sharpened those insights.
    </p><p>
      The findings were consistent: live sessions were slowed by hunt-and-peck
      navigation, most available data went untouched, and workarounds had become
      normalised.
    </p><p>
      Collaborating with the Directors of Field and Training, I led the review
      of the interface through the lens of the live session. We examined each
      on-screen element and asked whether it actively supported the interaction
      in the room.
    </p><p>
      <!-- Where it didn’t, it was removed or repositioned. -->
      The layout was simplified, prioritising glanceability, single-click input and
      ergonomics for standing use.
    </p>
  </section>
  <div class="image-row image-row--full">
    <Image
      src={updated311Image}
      alt="Updated screen designs"
      widths={[480, 768, 1024, 1440, 1920]}
      sizes="100vw"
    />
  </div>
  <div class="image-row--caption">
    <p>
      The redesign reduced on-screen data and clarified hierarchy, prioritising
      Navigation zones were expanded to reflect the ergonomics of one-handed,
      standing tablet use.
    </p>
    <p>Data entry was moved into context to minimise unnecessary navigation.</p>
    <p>
      Navigation zones were expanded to reflect the ergonomics of one-handed,
      standing tablet use.
    </p>
  </div>

  <section class="card content-block">
    <h2>Impact</h2>
    <p>
      I prototyped and usability tested the changes before development, reducing
      uncertainty ahead of build.
    </p>
    <p>
      Released as an optional setting (“classic” or “new”), the redesign saw
      over <strong>90% uptake</strong> within the first six weeks, enabling a smooth
      transition for Consultants. Site visit data indicated an improvement in Quality
      of Service following implementation.
    </p>
  </section>

  <h1 class="phase-title">
    <span>Phase 2</span>
  </h1>

  <section class="card content-block">
    <h2>Building on success</h2>
    <p>
      As Slimming World moved into a broader digital transformation, I led the
      experience design of the Consultant toolset, spanning member management,
      payments and financial administration, group preparation, in-session
      delivery and reporting, with the weekly group at its core.
    </p>
  </section>
  <div>
    <Image
      src={ecosystemImage}
      alt=""
      style="height:auto;"
      widths={[480, 768, 1024, 1440, 1920]}
      sizes="100vw"
    />
  </div>
  <p class="image-row--caption">
    My Consultant ecosystem map indicates the scale and scope of my role in the
    business' digital transformation. <br />The red circle highlights the
    subject of this article.
  </p>
  <section class="card content-block">
    <h2>Problem</h2>
    The member-support screens returned to executive focus, this time within the wider
    transformation programme and with broader stakeholder involvement. Early in the
    process, a clear position was stated:

    <h3 style="text-align:center; margin:var(--space-8) 0;">
      &ldquo;We&apos;re not changing the group process.&rdquo;
    </h3>
    <p>
      There was appetite to modernise the platform, but the live group model
      remained central to the business. The expectation was that technology
      should support it, not redefine it.
    </p>

    <p>
      A key part of my role was clarifying what that meant in practice.
      Establishing this boundary early helped frame decisions about what
      belonged on screen during the session.
    </p>
  </section>
  <section class="image-row image-row--full-bleed">
    <p class="image-overlay">Tap to view full map</p>
    <button
      class="lightbox-trigger"
      type="button"
      data-lightbox-target="journey-map"
      aria-label="Open journey map full size"
