    />
    <Image
      src={figmaMake3Image}
      alt=""
      widths={[480, 768, 1024, 1440, 1920]}
      sizes="100vw"
    />
  </section>
  <p class="image-row--caption">
    Rebuilding the prototype in Figma Make allowed for dynamic data sets and
    richer interactivity.
  </p>

  <section class="card content-block">
    <h2>Simulated group testing</h2>
    <p>
      To test the design in realistic conditions and build confidence across the
      organisation, I ran immersive simulated group sessions.
    </p>
    <p>
      Consultants used the prototype on tablet devices to run live support
      sessions, while colleagues from design, product, engineering and senior
      leadership role-played as members.
    </p><p>
      Testing revealed practical issues that hadn’t emerged in earlier prototype
      reviews. For example:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        Heavy use of red on the index screen amplified negative signals when
        overall group progress was low
      </li>
      <li>
        On-screen keyboard input disrupted conversation flow — replacing free
        text with selectors maintained engagement
      </li><li>
        Tap targets and interaction timing needed refinement to match live
        pacing
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Following several rounds of iteration, the design was signed off and moved
      into development, de-risked through early validation and strengthened by
      direct stakeholder participation.
    </p>
  </section>
  <section class="image-row">
    <!-- <img src="/images/xpress-weigh/figma/figma-make0.png" alt="" /> -->
    <Image
      src={tabletImage}
      alt="Tablet view"
      widths={[480, 768, 1024, 1440, 1920]}
      sizes="100vw"
    />
  </section>
  <p class="image-row--caption">
    Rebuilding the prototype in Figma Make enabled realistic data sets and
    richer interactivity, supporting live testing in realistic conditions.
  </p>

  <section class="card content-block">
    <h2>Impact & reflection</h2>

    <p>
      This work formed part of a wider transformation programme and was complex
      in its own right, shaped by deep organisational investment in the group
      model and an unexpected shift in how that model was delivered.
    </p>

    <p>
      Through sustained stakeholder engagement and research validation, I
      maintained focus on prioritisation and clarity as the scope evolved.
      Decisions were revisited where needed, but always tested against how they
      would perform in the live session.
    </p>

    <p>
      The design entered development signed-off, having been stress-tested under
      realistic conditions and reviewed with Consultants and senior
      stakeholders, including the board and Managing Director. It reduced
      ambiguity ahead of build and de-risked delivery through early validation
      and structured testing.
    </p>
    <hr class="divider" />
  </section>
